  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":334,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a fully conversational effort — you should be able to speak in full sentences. Aim for the middle of your easy pace range (5:04–5:34/km). This is aerobic base maintenance, not a test.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with 5 minutes of brisk walking and dynamic leg swings before easing into your easy pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5 minutes of easy walking and light calf and hip flexor stretches.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This run exists to accumulate aerobic volume without adding fatigue. Easy days done truly easy are what allow your quality sessions to land well. If you feel flat or tired, drift toward the slower end of the range — that's still great training.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Lactate Threshold Cruise Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":13,\"target_duration_minutes\":57,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":252,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km easy at 5:04–5:34/km. Finish with 4 strides of 20 seconds at a comfortably fast effort to prime your legs.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":252,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km at threshold pace (4:12/km). This should feel 'comfortably hard' — you can speak a word or two but not a full sentence. Controlled and steady.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"90 seconds to 2 minutes easy jog to recover between cruise intervals.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":252,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km at threshold pace (4:12/km). Maintain the same controlled effort as the first rep — resist the urge to push harder.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"90 seconds to 2 minutes easy jog.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":252,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km at threshold pace (4:12/km). Finish strong and controlled — this is the hardest part of the session.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km easy cooldown at 5:04–5:34/km. Let your breathing settle fully before stopping.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 km easy jog followed by 4 x 20-second strides. Do not skip the strides — they prepare your neuromuscular system for threshold effort.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3 km easy jog. Follow with standing quad stretch, calf raises, and hip flexor stretch held 30 seconds each side.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Cruise intervals at threshold pace are one of the highest-value sessions for marathon preparation. They raise your lactate threshold — the pace you can sustain for a long time before fatigue accumulates rapidly. The short recoveries between reps keep the physiological stimulus high while making the session manageable. Total threshold volume today is 8 km, which is a meaningful step up from your recent 6 km threshold blocks. The key is consistency of effort across all three reps — not a heroic final rep.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2max Kilometer Repeats\",\"target_distance_km\":14,\"target_duration_minutes\":60,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":234,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km easy at 5:04–5:34/km. Include 4–6 strides of 20 seconds at interval effort in the final 5 minutes to prime your cardiovascular system.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":25,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":234,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":6,\"notes\":\"6 x 1 km at interval pace (3:54/km) with 400m easy jog recovery between each rep. This pace should feel hard — you're working near your VO2max. Each rep should feel like a controlled effort you could repeat, not a sprint. If a rep feels significantly harder than the previous one, ease off slightly rather than blowing up.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":6,\"notes\":\"400m easy jog (approximately 2 minutes) between each kilometer repeat. Walk if needed — full recovery between reps is more important than keeping moving.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy cooldown at 5:04–5:34/km. Shake out your legs and let your heart rate drop fully.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 km easy jog with 4–6 x 20-second strides at the end. The strides are essential before interval work — they prepare your legs for the faster turnover.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2 km easy jog followed by full-body dynamic stretching. Pay particular attention to hip flexors and calves after interval work.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals are the engine-building sessions of your plan. Running at 3:54/km stresses your aerobic ceiling, which over weeks of training pushes that ceiling higher. This directly supports your 3:15 marathon goal by giving you a larger aerobic reserve to draw from on race day. You've done 6 x 1 km sessions recently, so this is a familiar stimulus — the goal this week is quality execution, not novelty. Saturday placement gives you a full day of rest before Sunday's long run.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run with Marathon Pace Finish\",\"target_distance_km\":27,\"target_duration_minutes\":145,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":268,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":354,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 2 km at the very easy end of your range (5:34/km or slower). Ease in gently — your body needs time to warm up on long runs.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":105,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Km 3 through 22 at easy aerobic pace (5:04–5:34/km). Stay conversational and relaxed. Nutrition: take a gel or equivalent carbohydrate source every 45 minutes from the 45-minute mark onward. Practice your race-day fueling strategy.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":22,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 5 km at marathon pace (4:28/km). This is the key stimulus of the session — running marathon pace on tired legs teaches your body to recruit efficiently when fatigued. Focus on form: tall posture, relaxed shoulders, quick cadence. This should feel controlled but purposeful.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":354,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk or very easy jog for 5–8 minutes after finishing. Do not stop abruptly after the marathon pace finish.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start conservatively — the first 2 km should feel almost too easy. Resist the urge to run faster early on a long run day.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5–8 minutes of easy walking followed by full lower body stretching: quads, hamstrings, calves, hip flexors. Consider a short foam roll session if available.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is the most important session of your week. At 27 km with a 5 km marathon-pace finish, it builds both the aerobic endurance and the specific fatigue resistance you'll need for a 3:15 marathon. The marathon-pace finish is a deliberate physiological tool — it trains your body to maintain goal pace when glycogen is depleted and fatigue is accumulating, which is exactly what kilometers 30–42 of your race will demand. Your recent long runs of 24 and 26 km show you're ready for this step. Keep your easy pace genuinely easy for the first 22 km so the marathon-pace finish is a quality stimulus, not a survival effort. Fueling during this run is non-negotiable — practice exactly what you plan to use on race day.\",\"perceived_effort\":8}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
